Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and dice @carrots{6%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut crosswise into ½-inch-thick half-moons. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

In a #small pot{}, combine @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, ¾ cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to a low simmer. Cook, covered, until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Toss carrots on one side of a #baking sheet{} (spread out across entire sheet for 4 servings) with a drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove sheet from oven. Toss zucchini on empty side with a drizzle of oil, salt, and pepper. (For 4, leave carrots roasting; toss zucchini on a second sheet and roast on middle rack.) Return to oven until veggies are tender and lightly browned, ~{10-15%minutes} more.

Let cool ~{2%minutes}; transfer veggies to a #medium bowl{}. Toss with lemon zest and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste.

Meanwhile, pat @pork chops{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with salt and pepper.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

Turn off heat; transfer pork to a #plate{} to rest.

In pan used for pork, stir in @Mike's Hot Honey{1}, @peach jam{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{2}, ¼ cup water (½ cup for 4 servings), and juice from one lemon wedge (two wedges for 4). Increase heat to medium high and bring sauce to a simmer. Cook, stirring constantly, until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4); season with salt and pepper.

Transfer pork to pan with sauce; turn to coat.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) and season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide rice, veggies, and pork between plates. Spoon any remaining sauce over pork. Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.